│ THOUGHT: I need to be more precise with my fix. Looking at the error case   │
│ again: we have 8-bit pointers, i32 elements (4 bytes each), and i8 indices. │
│ The issue is that even though the index is i8 (8 bits), when multiplied by  │
│ the element size (4), the effective offset can be up to 255*4=1020, which   │
│ requires more than 8 bits to represent, causing wrapping.                   │
│                                                                             │
│ The key insight is that for equality comparisons of GEPs with the same      │
│ base, the optimization `icmp eq (gep ptr, idx1), (gep ptr, idx2) -> icmp eq │
│ idx1, idx2` is only valid if the mapping from indices to pointer offsets is │
│ injective (one-to-one). This fails when pointer arithmetic wraps around.    │
│                                                                             │
│ A simpler and more robust approach is to check if the pointer size in bits  │
│ is greater than or equal to the maximum possible bits needed to represent   │
│ any offset. However, this is complex to compute exactly.                    │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking at LLVM's existing code patterns, a common approach is to check if  │
│ the GEP has no-wrap flags OR if the pointer size is "large enough". For the │
│ specific case in the bug report (8-bit pointers), we should definitely not  │
│ perform this optimization.                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ Let me implement a simpler conservative check: if the pointer size in bits  │
│ is less than or equal to the size of the largest index type plus some bits  │
│ for element size scaling, don't fold.                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ Actually, let me look at how other parts of LLVM handle similar issues. The │
│ most conservative and correct approach for now is to only allow folding     │
│ equality comparisons when there are no-wrap flags present, since that's the │
│ only guarantee we have that wrapping won't occur.                           │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ cp                                                                          │
│ /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCom │
│ pares.cpp /tmp/InstCombineCompares.cpp.bak2 && sed -i '691,700d'            │
│ /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCom │
│ pares.cpp && cat <<'EOF' >>                                                 │
│ /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCom │
│ pares.cpp                                                                   │
│   auto CanFold = [Cond](GEPNoWrapFlags NW) {                                │
│     if (ICmpInst::isEquality(Cond)) {                                       │
│       // For equality comparisons, we can only safely fold if the GEP has   │
│ no-wrap                                                                     │
│       // flags that guarantee no pointer wrapping can occur.                │
│       // Without no-wrap flags, pointer arithmetic may wrap (especially     │
│ with                                                                        │
│       // small pointer sizes like 8-bit pointers), making different indices │
│       // produce the same pointer value.                                    │
│       return NW != GEPNoWrapFlags::none();                                  │
│     }                                                                       │
│                                                                             │
│     // Unsigned predicates can be folded if the GEPs have *any* nowrap      │
│ flags.                                                                      │
│     assert(ICmpInst::isUnsigned(Cond));                                     │
│     return NW != GEPNoWrapFlags::none();                                    │
│   };                                                                        │
│ EOF                                                                         │
