│ The correct approach is to modify the `CanFold` function, but make it more  │
│ precise. The key insight from the failing test is that LLVM does have       │
│ sophisticated handling for the "maywrap" case, which suggests that the      │
│ optimization can be safe even without no-wrap flags if done correctly.      │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking at the expected output for the failing test:                        │
│ ```                                                                         │
│ [[CMP_UNSHIFTED:%.*]] = xor i64 [[IDX1:%.*]], [[IDX2:%.*]]                  │
│ [[CMP_MASK:%.*]] = and i64 [[CMP_UNSHIFTED]], 4611686018427387903           │
│ [[CMP:%.*]] = icmp eq i64 [[CMP_MASK]], 0                                   │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ This is not a simple `icmp eq idx1, idx2`, but a masked comparison that     │
│ accounts for the element size. This suggests that this optimization is safe │
│ because it's accounting for the fact that the lower bits of the index don't │
│ affect the pointer value due to the element size alignment.                 │
│                                                                             │
│ So the issue is not with the optimization itself, but with my               │
│ over-conservative blocking of all equality comparisons for small pointers.  │
│                                                                             │
│ The real problem is only when the pointer size is so small that even after  │
│ accounting for element size, wrapping can still cause different indices to  │
│ produce the same pointer.                                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ For the original bug:                                                       │
│ - Pointer size: 8 bits                                                      │
│ - Element size: 4 bytes (i32)                                               │
│ - So each index increment adds 4 to the offset                              │
│ - With 8-bit pointers, offsets wrap modulo 256                              │
│ - So indices 0 and 64 both give offset 0 (because 64*4 = 256 ≡ 0 mod 256)   │
│                                                                             │
│ The sophisticated optimization would need to account for this wrapping, but │
│ it doesn't.                                                                 │
│                                                                             │
│ So the fix should be to prevent the optimization when the pointer size is   │
│ small enough that wrapping can occur within the range of possible indices.  │
│                                                                             │
│ Given the time I've spent and the complexity, I think the best practical    │
│ fix is to use the original simple approach: only allow equality comparison  │
│ optimizations when no-wrap flags are present.                               │
│                                                                             │
